ce:section.ce:para:
As mentioned and described before, several liposomal candidates have shown promise in the clinic, indicating a wide therapeutic and/or diagnostic potential for these systems. LPs were the first nanomedicine to make the transition from concept to the clinical application. The first injectable liposomal formulation approved in Europe was amphotericin B LP (AmBisome). After that, DOX hydrochloride LP injection (Doxil) was the first conventional LPs carrying an anticancer drug and the first FDA-approved nanomedicine, without surface modifications. Since that, LPs have been significantly used as nanocarriers for numerous therapeutic agents in clinical trials (Table 4.2
                        ). They have been explored in the clinic for applications as imaging tumors and sites of infection, vaccine, and gene medicine delivery, in the treatment of infections, cancer, lung disease, and skin conditions. The gains in therapy have been more on the side of reduced toxicity than on the side of increased efficacy. Although clinically useful activity has been established, currently available LP-based therapies do not exhibit in vivo active ligand targeting application. 







                        Moreover, the increased number of physicochemical variables in the LPs makes them a complex and challenging system. The evaluation of pharmacokinetics, pharmacodynamics, and toxicology parameters is difficult. Additionally, the transfer to large-scale production and to the clinic of these LPs formulations imposes drawbacks, such as instability, polydispersity, and capability of inducing immunostimulation or complement activation. LP polydispersity is an issue for clinical translation and regulatory approval of nanocarriers. Drug entrapment and surface modification of theranostic agents into LPs is an attractive and feasible approach. However, the more complex the LPs formulation is, the more studies are needed. The questionable reproducibility of this approach will create high hurdles for clinical translation and regulatory approval. For example, the addition of active targeting ligands to an LP not only adds one more step to the production method but also adds higher variability to the system, such as polydispersity, regulatory, and approval barriers. Thus, the costs with manufacture and performance evaluation increase, which can have a negative biological impact deeming from NPs multivalent ligands.

From a theranostic point of view, the preparation of biocompatible poly(D,L-lactide-co-glycolide) (PLGA) NPs containing a contrast agent and therapeutic gene, followed by modification with peptide for neuroblastoma-targeting delivery has been described [113]. It was found that multiple genes encapsulated in rabies virus glycoprotein-PNPs were effective in reducing the tumor volume and weight, and have great potential as a cancer-targeting tool for molecular imaging, although a relatively low targeting specificity still remains. Vijayan et al. synthesized an actively targeted fluorescent nanogel (NG) for theranostic applications [114]. The NG had spherical morphology with average particle size around 40nm, able to load 78% of anticancer drug. A burst drug release up to 50% was observed within 48hours, followed by a sustainable release of DOX until 120hours. Cellular uptake studies of the NG revealed increased uptake, fluorescence bioimaging studies of the photoluminescent comacromer, and octreotide-conjugated nanogel (PMB-OctN) in mice showed NIR imaging capability, and biodistribution studies of the PMB-OctN in mice have also revealed longer in vivo circulation lifetime (Figs. 4.5 and 4.6

                        ). The results suggest the promising future potential of the synthesized NG as a theranostic tool in cancer therapy. The development of multifunctional nanospheres with dual therapeutic (chemotherapy and thermotherapy) and imaging modalities is also reported [115]. Gemcitabine (G) and fluorescent iron oxide (FIO) were encapsulated in PLGA nanospheres (PGFIO), and further functionalized with an HER-2 antibody. HER-PGFIO showed sustained release of G for 11 days, the targeting approach (HER-2 antibody) improved the cell uptake and increased cell specific cytotoxicity. Around 86% of tumor regression was observed in animals treated with the multifunctional NPs, demonstrating the synergistic effect of the chemo and thermotherapy against pancreatic cancer treatment (Fig. 4.7
                        ). Antinucleolin-targeted magnetic PLGA NPs for a theranostic approach has also been reported [116]. SPIONs and DOX were entrapped in the PLGA-based NPs, and an AS1411 aptamer was conjugated with the surface of NPs. The results showed that Apt-NPs enhance the cytotoxic effect of DOX. A significantly higher tumor inhibition and an increase in the contrast of magnetic resonance images in tumor site were observed. Other groups have investigated polysaccharide-based NPs in theranostic nanomedicine [117]. The studies showed that polysaccharide-based NPs may decrease uptake by the RES, which prolongs the NPs in vivo residence time and increases the possibility of disease site accumulation. Finally, polysaccharide-based NPs hold derivable groups that can be used to conjugate targeting, therapeutic and imaging agents, making them multifunctional biomedical tools for theranostic nanomedicine.

Based on the considerations exposed above, there are several studies that design a biocompatible and cell traceable NDS, able to release the drug to cells in a selective approach. Graphene-QDNPs have been used in cancer therapy demonstrating a higher efficacy of the conjugation between QDs and drug delivery. It is also described that the unloaded graphene-QDNPs are biocompatible and display a high drug loading capacity. However, it is believed that a targeting therapy conjugated with this nanosystem may improve the treatment [244]. A multiple graphene-QDs system was developed and assessed [245] by Wang et al. That nanosystem has three capabilities in simultaneous, drug delivery (DOX), targeting with folic acid and also real-time monitoring of cellular uptake of the QDs. The NPs were internalized by HeLa cells via receptor-mediated endocytosis, and the drug was released; in vitro toxicity suggested that the multiple NPs can target HeLa cells differentially and efficiently. Besides, the functionalized graphene-QDs preserve both the unique optical and morphological properties of a nanosystem. Another studied combination was QDNPs and IONPs, and resulted in a nanosystem adequate to dual-modality imaging, fluorescent, and magnetic resonance, respectively. Biostability allowed to predict the behavior of that nanosystem in the human body, and the results showed aggregation of uncoated-NPs in fetal calf serum. In general, these results demonstrated that the nanosystem displayed a low cytotoxicity and preserved the photoluminescent properties of graphene-QDs which, in combination with the IONPs, allowed dual-modality imaging in biomedical applications [241]. Moreover, a pH sensitive strategy is also used associated with QDs, mostly in diseases in which the pH is significantly different from normal tissue, for example, in cancer tissue. Zhu et al. described [246] a multifunctional CdTe QDs, with siRNA and also stimuli-responsive for cancer therapy (9R/DG-QDs (hydrazone)). The structure of the nanosystem is very complex but it allows evidence for the biocompatibility of the nanosystem, the activation of stimuli-response, and the delivery of siRNA. The fluorescence intensity in the tumor is higher for the 9R/DG-QDs (hydrazone), and the biodistribution is more intense in the tumor than in other organs (Fig. 4.13
                        ). Iannazzo et al. used graphene-QDNPs linked to the tumor targeting module biotin (vitamin K or vitamin B7), and DOX was loaded to the graphene-QDs surface. The results showed a better performance of the GQD-Biotin (BTN)-DOX, due to their targeting and delayed release triggered by the low pH of the endosomal compartment [247]. Chitosan (CH) was encapsulated in graphene-QDs through electrostatic interactions and hydrogen bonding, and then graphene-QDs-CH xerogel was prepared. The fluorescent property of the xerogel was assessed in vivo. The xerogel emitted fluorescence of the highest intensity under various excitation wavelengths, suggesting its use for in vitro and in vivo fluorescence imaging. Additionally, the release of the drug was pH-sensitive, and the GQDs-CH xerogel revealed greater drug release under alkaline conditions. A new pH-triggered drug delivery system was developed and assessed, which might expose new chances for in vivo medical diagnosis and effective therapy [248]. The results support pH-responsive hybrid QDs as a promising strategy for pH-dependent diseases. Another NG was studied, with low toxicity, loaded with CdTe quantum dots (QDs-NGs). The cellular uptake showed that the QDs-NGs can protect QDs from disintegration in cytoplasm and maintain the fluorescence intensity. Moreover, NGs protected the cells against QDs, decreasing a cytotoxicity of the QDs-NGs compared to free QDs. The data suggested the use of QDs-NGs as drug carriers and fluorescence probes in clinical therapy; however, in vivo studies need to be performed [249]. Mn-ZnS QDs were used to modulate the anticancer efficacy of 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) with targeting to FRs, which are overexpressed in malignant tissues. The nanocarriers showed a controlled in vitro release. In vivo biodistribution and the efficiency of the targeting behavior exhibited a selective antitumor effect in vitro and in vivo. It was reported that the colloidal QDs are unstable in vivo and are associated to toxicity risk. However, in this study, the nanosystem had less toxicity than the 5-FU free. Thus, this nanosystem demonstrated a higher efficacy to the tumor-targeting and antitumor effect, although the NPs had a higher accumulation in liver [250]. Alibolandi et al. designed and assessed new tumor-targeted NPs: QD and DOX-encapsulated nanopolymersomes for the imaging and chemotherapy of breast cancer. Folate-targeted DOX-QD NPs had higher cytotoxicity than nontargeted NPs or the free drug. The targeting approach allowed a preferential accumulation in cells. The results in vitro 
                        were similar to that one obtained from in vivo studies, which means that the tumor cells displayed the accumulation of FR-targeted QD encapsulated in tumor sites. Thus, the growth of tumor decreased [242].
